column72: feedback. Here, you can give open feedback regarding concerns, improvement proposals and other thoughts.
I thought the vehicle was driving too quickly through the train station. There were pedestrians crossing the road in front of the car. The car ultimately didn't hit anyone, but it made me nervous.
The system had a lot of trouble understanding the pedestrians' intents and to even recognize some of them. It really made me anxious.
i would like to see turn signals and the vehicle comes rather close to others when stopping.
I feel tense regarding the pedestrians, who are not always correctly gauged.
Nothing comes to mind the car was detecting things very easily, it was highlighting pedestrians quickly and also tracking signs/lights fast.

Some of the pedestrians prediction seemed off or delayed. Also, bikes were shown as pedestrians when no one was riding or near them. I don't know if that is what it is supposed to recognize. There was one time where I felt a pedestrian could have walked in front of the automated vehicle at a crosswalk where the vehicle paused but then continued on while a group of pedestrians were standing there.

Fun study! The first study I took was a bit more easy to understand  the pathway or movement of the car, I mean like the pedestrian signs above the people were a bit harder to understand this time. I thought it was dark blue means stationary or not going in your path, light blue means they are going to walk in you're path and the other color means unknown. I will research more prior to the next study so I can be fully informed. Great visuals, felt like I was actually there in the car, I assumed I was driving or automatically driving in Germany? Great experience! I will see you guys on the next study tomorrow morning!
I obtained my driver's license in Canada, and the roads, traffic lights and signs were slightly different than what I have experienced

How does the visual react during rainy days? Does it interfere especially among individuals that carries an umbrella? I noticed that at certain areas of the video, there were alot of people and the visuals were accurately displaying their movements, but I am curious to know if this technology could work during heavy rain or snow.
I would like to see how the vehicle would react if a pedestrian would jump out, or if something out of the ordinary would happen.

I did notice that in some situations there would be a reflection of a car or pedestrian in a window or road divider but the car would not highlight such reflections; no concern, just something notable.
I don't have any additional feedback at this time.
There is still too much going on with the pedestrian signs changing so rapidly that its confusing.

I felt there were a few instances where I wasn't entirely sure if a pedestrian was in a truly safe position. As you are unable to see past the edge of the screen or along the side of the vehicle, it is sometimes hard to truly visualize all perspectives. I felt there was perhaps a few more close calls regarding pedestrians, but perhaps if I'd been able to see out the side window, I wouldn't have been as concerned.

I did feel the deceleration and acceleration when stopping and starting was better paced. While I do still find the colors and indicators as to pedestrian actions somewhat distracting, I feel I am getting a bit more familiar with the system the vehicle is using.
car could have stopped a little further back from the stop lines/lights
